ontprox takes the OWL ontology (in our case OKH),
and whenever someone requests it over HTTP(S),
It gets converted on-the-fly into the requested format,
but also users of RDF data,
whether they are concious about it or not.
This circle is the ontology development workflow.
Linters (executed on CI) give ideas to the Ontology developer
for how to improve the ontology,
while the pretty printer should be used before each commit
by said dev on hi/her machine, locally,
and on CI as well, to ensure it was used.
This provides an extensive general quality control system for ontologies,
similar to what devs are already used to,
The LOV website (global registry of ontologies) uses the same/similar tools,
so this quality control will then find recognition by the autside world,
investigating the ontolgy through their site.
